1. Construct the set $P'=\{(c_{1}, c_{2}, \cdots, c_{n-t+1}) |(c_{1}, c_{2}, \cdots, c_{n-t+1}, \cdots, c_{n}) \in P\}$, that is, form a new set $P'$ by taking the first $n-t+1$ components of each element in P;
2. Prove $|P'|=|P|$: on the one hand, $|P'|≤|P|$ is obvious; on the other hand, assume that there are two different elements A and B in P whose first $n-t+1$ components are exactly the same, then $d(A,B)≤t-1$, which contradicts the fact that the minimum distance between any two elements in P is t. Therefore, the first $n-t+1$ components of different elements in P must be different, that is, $|P'|≥|P|$, so $|P'|=|P|=m$;
3. Since the elements in $P'$ are $n-t+1$-dimensional vectors composed of 0 and 1, the maximum number of its elements is $2^{n-t+1}$, that is, $|P'|≤2^{n-t+1}$;
4. Combined with $|P'|=m$, it can be obtained that $m ≤2^{n-t+1}$, and the proof is completed.
